[2]
From: "Dr. R.D. Paskin" <paskin@iafrica.com.na>
Date: Sun, 31 Aug 1997 12:25:46 +0200
In a time when beef-exporting countries in southern Africa are coming under
increasing pressure from EU countries to prove their freedom from BSE, the
item on BSE under-reporting by these same countries makes revealing
reading. I heard a rumour recently of so-called "bulldozer disease" in
France - when cattle show nervous signs, farmers apparently use bulldozers
to bury them for fear BSE might be diagnosed. Can this be true?
---
Roger Paskin
Animal Health Surveillance Unit
Windhoek, NAMIBIA
paskin@iafrica.com.na
*****
[3]
Date: Fri, 29 Aug 1997 17:51:18 +0100
From: Oz <Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk>
>The report calculates that of the 55,400 British cattle exported to other
>EU countries for breeding purposes between 1985 and 1989, at least 1,642
>would have contracted BSE after export. However, only 285 cases were
reported.
Actually, of course, it's very much worse than this. A considerable
number of live finished cattle were also exported in that period. I
don't have the figures to hand but I am confident the number was very
many times the number for breeding cattle. One presumes their remains
were made into MBM which was fed on the continent (as occurred in the
UK) but this MBM seems to have been strangely uninfectious.
>In Germany - where the campaign against buying British beef has been
>strongest - the number of BSE cases reported since March last year was 48
>times less than expected.
This was utterly predictable (in all EU countries, not just Germany) due to
the unscientific [herd depopulation is a well recognized disease control
option, so why is it unscientific - mod pc] practice of slaughtering whole
herds where a case was found (in the case of Germany, whole breeds). Not
only does this have a negligeable effect on reducing new cases, it pretty
well ensures that a farmer will endevour to conceal cases. This was
predicted by SEAC and even by the UK members of parliament (well known for
their towering intellect) at the very start of the epidemic in the UK.
--
O. Hotz de Baar
Impoverished Farmer.
Southern England, UK.
...............................................pc

